y care trusts (PCTs) to NHS England from April 2013.</p><p>In addition, responsibility for public health and prevention programme moved from PCTs to local authorities.</p><p>Source: Rows 1, 2, 3 -Primary Care expenditure Departmental accounts; row 4 - Other Programme Budgeting NHS England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","34010","2016-04-21T14:04:11.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513016/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513016/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of dental practices which were accepting NHS patients in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","34058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513017","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34054 ; 34055 ; 34076 ; 34077 ; 34078 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:49.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513017/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513017/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether Lancashire Teaching Hospitals Trust, working with a clinical commissioning group, has asked every GP in Lancashire if it can help cover the staff shortfall in that trust.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513018","Department of Health","false","2016-04-22","<p>It is estimated that there are around 120,000 people living in the United Kingdom who survived polio when they were younger. Although some of these have or will develop post-polio syndrome (PPS), it is not known exactly how many polio survivors are affected and estimates vary.</p><p> </p><p>Commissioning of services for PPS is a local matter. People with PPS can usually be managed through routine access to primary or second care provided via a general practitioner (GP) or consultant. Treatment will depend on the severity of a patient’s condition, but care may involve: pain relieving medication; physiotherapy; dietary and exercise advice; and counselling or cognitive behavioural therapy.</p><p> </p><p>Although not currently funding any research into PPS, the National Institute for Health Research welcomes funding applications for research into any aspect of human health, including PPS. These applications are subject to peer review and judged in open competition, with awards being made on the basis of the importance of the topic to patients and health and care services, value for money and scientific quality.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-22T13:07:27.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513018/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513018/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Post-polio Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people in the UK who are affected by post-polio syndrome; what steps are being taken to fund (a) treatment of and (b) research into that condition; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","34129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513019","Department of Health","false","2016-04-22","<p>The planning of the process to select test sites, including timing and criteria for selection, will continue alongside NHS England’s review of its position on the commissioning of pre-exposure prophyaxis (PrEP).</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-22T13:06:13.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513019/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513019/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which areas have been chosen as test sites for the pre-exposure drug prophyaxis (PrEP); what selection criteria have been used to identify those test sites; and what measures his Department plans to use to assess the effectiveness of PrEP in the test sites over the next two years.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","34127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513020","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The main costs associated with the consultation on reform of the infected blood payment schemes were for printing of the consultation document and postage of letters to inform all 3,482 scheme registrants, and 180 hon. Members, of the launch of the consultation. This amounted to £7,177 and was taken from the Department’s own budgets. A core team of three civil servants, with senior management input, is developing the new payment scheme and the consultation is integral to their work. Thirteen additional staff members, from across the Department, are helping to analyse the consultation responses.</p><p>Information on the respondents’ status was collected as part of the consultation but it was not obligatory to provide it and neither was it collected in the way asked in this question.</p><p>Consultation responses are still being analysed, however to date, the number of respondents by category are;</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>I have hepatitis C (from infected National Health Service supplied blood/blood products)</p></td><td><p>894</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>I am HIV positive (from infected NHS supplied blood/blood products)</p></td><td><p>101</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>I am immediate family (a widow, partner, child or parent) of someone infected with hepatitis C, HIV or both by an NHS blood/blood product</p></td><td><p>277</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>I am a carer for a person infected with hepatitis C, HIV or both by an NHS supplied blood/blood products)</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Prefer not to say</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>165</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not answered</p></td><td><p>50</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-21T14:18:05.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513020/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513020/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost of his Department's recent consultation on infected blood was; how many responses that consultation received from (a) people with Stage 1 hepatitis C, (b) people with Stage 2 hepatitis C, (c) people with HIV, (d) people with HIV and hepatitis C, (e) the widows and widowers of those affected and (f) other people; and how many full-time equivalent staff have been allocated to running that consultation.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","34131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513021","Department of Health","false","2016-04-22","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Community pharmacies already take significant steps to care for patients with long term conditions (LTCS). Community pharmacy staff routinely deliver a range of services to meet the needs of patients with LTCs, including timely dispensing of medicines, opportunistic and prescription-linked public health interventions, such as advice on a healthy diet and nutrition, stop smoking advice to help maintain the health of people with LTCs such as diabetes and heart disease, support for self-care and signposting, when they are not able to provide the support themselves.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, community pharmacists provide advice on the safe use of medicines so they are taken as intended, through medicines use reviews and the new medicines service, the latter intended for people with certain LTCs prescribed new medicines. Utilising pharmacists clinical skills assists with optimising medicines in a way which puts patients at the centre of decision making, with regular monitoring and review, helping to improve their health outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s vision is for a more efficient, modern system that will free up pharmacists to spend more time delivering clinical and public health services to the benefit of patients, including those with LTCs, and the public.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-22T09:31:02.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513021/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513021/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Chronic Illnesses: Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to allow community pharmacies to care for patients with long-term health conditions through (a) medical reviews and (b) other assistance with that condition.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","34116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513022","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34054 ; 34055 ; 34056 ; 34076 ; 34078 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:49.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513022/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513022/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Chorley and South Ribble Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps were taken to address the risk of staff shortages at Chorley and South Ribble Accident & Emergency unit; and when such steps were reported to (a) the Trust Board, (b) Monitor, (c) the clinical commissioning group and (d) his Department.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513023","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34054 ; 34055 ; 34056 ; 34076 ; 34077 ; 34078 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:49.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513023/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513023/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Chorley and South Ribble Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when (a) the fact of, (b) the reasons for and (c) consequences of shortages of staff at Chorley and South Ribble Accident and Emergency unit was first reported to (i) him, (ii) the Trust Board, (iii) Monitor, (iv) the Clinical Commissioning Group and (v) the Department of Health.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513024","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre does not hold the data to answer this question as the identification of intersex people is not possible within the Mental Health Services Data Set.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-19T15:57:19.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513024/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513024/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Mental Health Services: Intersex","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many intersex people have been referred for or requested mental health support in England in each year since 2010; and how many clinical commissioning groups commission specialised mental health support for intersex (a) children and (b) adults.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","34103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513025","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Department does not collect this information centrally.</p><p>No formal statistics are collected of autism referrals, initial assessments or diagnoses. The Department does however commission Public Health England each year to carry out a self-assessment exercise with local authority areas on progress they are making in implementing the Autism Strategy for Adults in England.</p><p>NHS England has almost completed a programme to visit clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to identify and share good practice in accessing timely autism diagnosis. NHS England with support from the Association of Directors of Adult Social Services has visited a selection of areas to talk to CCGs and local authorities about their Autism Diagnostic Care Pathways and post diagnostic support. A report on this work will go initially to the June meeting of the Cross Government Autism Programme Board.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-19T15:59:12.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513025/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513025/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Autism: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting time for children between referral for an autism diagnosis and first diagnostic appointment was in each clinical commissioning group and primary care trust area in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","34105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513026","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34054 ; 34055 ; 34056 ; 34076 ; 34077 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:49.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513026/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513026/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Chorley and South Ribble Hospital: Doctors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what attempts have been made to begin a national media campaign to recruit doctors at Chorley and South Ribble District Hospital; and in which national papers that campaign was placed.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513027","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34055 ; 34056 ; 34076 ; 34077 ; 34078 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:49.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513027/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513027/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Accident and Emergency Departments: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what Lancashire Teaching Hospitals Trust's Business Resilience Plan is to avoid acute shortages of staff at the Accident and Emergency department.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513028","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>This data has not been collected centrally before January 2016. However, in February this year for the first time the Health and Social Care Information Centre began collecting a range of data about children and young people’s use of secondary mental health services via the new Mental Health Services Dataset. This includes data on waiting times from referral to treatment in child and adolescent mental health services. Data quality and quantity will take time to build, but we expect a range of national reports to be developed during the course of 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-19T10:54:29.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513028/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513028/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average number of days was from referral to treatment in child and adolescent mental health services in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","34104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513029","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34054 ; 34055 ; 34056 ; 34076 ; 34077 ; 34078","2016-04-19T10:56:49.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513029/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513029/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Trust: Doctors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether Lancashire Teaching Hospitals Trust, working with a Clinical Commissioning Group, has worked with Medex or other private companies embedded within the HR department to recruit doctors.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513030","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34054 ; 34056 ; 34076 ; 34077 ; 34078 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:49.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513030/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513030/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513030/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Chorley and South Ribble Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether Lancashire Teaching Hospitals Trust has a Risk Register covering staffing at the Accident and Emergency department at Chorley and South Ribble District Hospital.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513031","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Government’s Mandate to NHS England sets out an expectation for NHS England to achieve measurable progress towards the parity of esteem for mental health enshrined in the NHS Constitution. Progress is being monitored as part of NHS England’s planning and financial reporting process.</p><p><em>Delivering the Forward View: NHS planning guidance for 2016-17</em> requires clinical commissioning groups (CCG) to increase investment in mental health services above their overall increase in allocation each year. This can include investment in primary or secondary mental health services, which should be aligned with delivery of the <em>Five Year Forward View for Mental Health: a report from the Independent Mental Health Taskforce</em> published in February 2016.</p><p>Where a CCG is not investing in mental health services as planned and without providing adequate justification, NHS England will work with the CCG to bring their spending back in line with their plan.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-21T14:00:47.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513031/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513031/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Mental Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that all clinical commissioning groups increase investment in mental health services each year at a level which at least matches their overall expenditure increase.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","34094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513032","Department of Health","false","2016-04-20","<p>Since the community pharmacy contractual framework was introduced in 2005, the usual practice has been to set one year funding settlements for community pharmacy. As previously announced, the funding for community pharmacy for 2016/17 is £2.63 billion. Discussions are being held with the Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee, which represents pharmacy owners.</p><p>We cannot comment further on future funding at this time.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-20T09:38:39.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513032/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513032/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Pharmacy: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much has been allocated to the community pharmacy contractual framework in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","34093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513033","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>These are operational matters for the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust and we have written to Stuart Heys, Chair of the Trust informing him of the hon. Member’s questions. He will reply shortly and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Library.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34053 ; 34054 ; 34055 ; 34056 ; 34077 ; 34078 ; 34079","2016-04-19T10:56:48.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513033/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513033/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Chorley and South Ribble Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the Chief Executive of the Lancashire Teaching Hospitals Trust has made a request to (a) the military and (b) the Cabinet Office to fully cover the 24 hour accident and emergency service at Chorley and South Ribble Accident & Emergency unit.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513034","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>We routinely monitor all licensed sponsors to ensure they are meeting their duties and responsibilities. This includes undertaking visits to sponsors to inspect their compliance with the sponsor guidance. All visits to sponsors are undertaken according to published guidance which is available at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/points-based-system-sponsor-management</p><p>We are, however, unable to comment on specific cases.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-21T11:58:45.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513034/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513034/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 April 2016 to Question 32350, how many compliance visits have been carried out on Tier 2 ICT visa recipients employed by Tata Consulting Services in the UK over the last 12 months; and what aspects of employment were assessed on those compliance visits.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","34096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513035","Home Office","false","2016-04-28","<p>In 2015 227 compliance visits were undertaken to Tier 2 sponsors who have the ability to sponsor individuals under the Tier 2 ICT route.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-28T12:22:21.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513035/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513035/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 11 April 2016 to Question 32350, how many compliance visits per employer that have taken place on Tier 2 ICT visa workers in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","34097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513036","Home Office","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government works closely with all carriers, not just British registered carriers, to connect their systems to the Government’s border systems to ensure those connections are operating properly and to ensure that any IT problems are identified and resolved. Should any circumstance arise where a carrier should have refused authority to carry an individual to the UK, that individual will be met on arrival. Border Force also conducts 100% checks at passport control on all passengers arriving in the UK by commercial air, rail or maritime services at passport controls. This includes screening against watch lists.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34099 ; 34117","2016-04-28T12:24:02.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513036/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513036/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on whether any failure of IT systems on UK-based airlines has allowed any individual on her Department's no fly list to travel in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","34098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513037","Home Office","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government works closely with all carriers, not just British registered carriers, to connect their systems to the Government’s border systems to ensure those connections are operating properly and to ensure that any IT problems are identified and resolved. Should any circumstance arise where a carrier should have refused authority to carry an individual to the UK, that individual will be met on arrival. Border Force also conducts 100% checks at passport control on all passengers arriving in the UK by commercial air, rail or maritime services at passport controls. This includes screening against watch lists.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34098 ; 34117","2016-04-28T12:24:02.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513037/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513037/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on whether any failure of IT systems on UK-based airlines led to passenger flight lists not being cross-referenced with her Department's (a) no fly list and (b) other relevant information in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","34099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513038","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service is a non-departmental public body which provides access to appropriate criminal record information for employers through its disclosure service for England and Wales. It also makes independent barring decisions about people who have harmed, or where there is considered to be a risk of harm to, a child or vulnerable person within the workplace. Given the sensitive nature of this work and the reliance on police forces to provide locally held intelligence, it would not be appropriate to introduce competition.</p><p>Whilst no assessment has been made of the affect of timeliness on the number of job opportunities which may have been lost, the impact which delays may have on applicants is recognised. The DBS is reliant on police forces completing their checks in a timely manner and is working closely with those forces whose performance does not meet turnaround time targets. In very exceptional cases, where it is apparent that a delay is likely to cause undue hardship to an applicant, the DBS will do all it can to expedite the process by raising an escalation with the relevant police force.</p><p>The average end to end time taken to complete a DBS check, including the time taken by police forces, is listed in following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Average calendar days for a disclosure to be processed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>11.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14/15</p></td><td><p>14.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15/16</p></td><td><p>14.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The proportion of checks which took longer than (a) eight weeks (b) 12 weeks and (c) six months is listed in the following table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Disclosures which took longer than 8 weeks</p></td><td><p>Disclosures which took longer than 12 weeks</p></td><td><p>Disclosures which took longer than 6 Months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% of Disclosures</p></td><td><p>% of Disclosures</p></td><td><p>% of Disclosures</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>2.6%</p></td><td><p>0.8%</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14/15</p></td><td><p>4.9%</p></td><td><p>2.1%</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15/16</p></td><td><p>5.2%</p></td><td><p>3.5%</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","34032 ; 34033 ; 34034","2016-04-21T11:55:52.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513038/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513038/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of introducing competition into the Disclosure and Barring Service; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","34035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513039","Home Office","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government works closely with all carriers, not just British registered carriers, to connect their systems to the Government’s border systems to ensure those connections are operating properly and to ensure that any IT problems are identified and resolved. Should any circumstance arise where a carrier should have refused authority to carry an individual to the UK, that individual will be met on arrival. Border Force also conducts 100% checks at passport control on all passengers arriving in the UK by commercial air, rail or maritime services at passport controls. This includes screening against watch lists.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34098 ; 34099","2016-04-28T12:24:02.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513039/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513039/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Aviation: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what procedures her Department has to ensure that aviation watch lists are cross-referenced with passenger manifests; and what steps her Department takes in instances of failure of such procedures.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","34117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513040","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>Breast ironing is a form of so called 'honour-based' violence (HBV) and this Government is clear that political or cultural sensitivities must not get in the way of preventing and uncovering practices like breast ironing. No one should suffer because of who they are or which community they are born into.</p><p>As set out in the Government’s new Violence against Women and Girls Strategy, we will continue to challenge the cultural attitudes that may underpin harmful practices, and ensure professionals have the confidence to confront these issues, safeguard victims and bring perpetrators to justice.</p><p>Where breast ironing is practised on girls it is child abuse and should be treated as such by all frontline professionals. The clear legal frameworks that apply to child abuse apply to breast ironing.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-04-19T13:36:35.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513040/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513040/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Breast Ironing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to prevent the practice of breast ironing in UK communities.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","34114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513041","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>Since 2009, under section 19(2)(a) of the Inquiries Act 2005,the Secretary of State for the Home Department has issued a total of four restriction notices - two in 2014 and two in 2015. All four were in relation to the Litvinenko Inquiry.</p><p>The Secretary of State for the Home Department has not issued any restriction notices for the Undercover Policing Inquiry.</p><p>Under section 19(2)(b) of the Inquiries Act 2005 restriction orders can only be issued by the Chair of an inquiry.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-19T13:36:55.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513041/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513041/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Inquiries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many restriction (a) notices and (b) orders her Department has issued to restrict inquiries under (i) section 19(1)(a) and (ii) section 19(1)(b) of the Inquiries Act 2005 in each year since 2009-10 (A) in total and (B) for the Undercover Policing Inquiry.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","34132"
