"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513048","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>At the Spending Review in December 2015, the Chancellor announced a major investment of £143 million to uplift armed policing capacity to respond more quickly and effectively to a marauding firearms attack.</p><p>The police have been working to allocate that spending to ensure maximum effect and are arranging for sufficient instructors and training places to be in place.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-04-19T13:29:46.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513048/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513048/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Police: Firearms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect on the ratio of firearms instructors to police officers of the Government's policy to train an extra 1,500 firearms officers by April 2018.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","34147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513049","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>In the context of warranted officers and in relation to the Policing and Crime Bill, “warranted” means attested as a constable. The Bill sets out a series of reforms, endorsed in a public consultation, that will enhance the powers of chief police officers to designate police staff and volunteers with a broad range of powers or duties, other than those core powers that will be available only to constables. In making this distinction, we are underlining the central place of the constable in policing.</p><p>These reforms will free up police officers to concentrate on the core policing tasks that most require their particular powers and experience, while enabling chief police officers to deploy a flexible and balanced workforce with the appropriate mix of skills and experience to keep our communities safe. We know there is demand from forces to introduce these volunteer roles – Lincolnshire, for example, have already recruited and trained volunteer Police Community Support Officers, who are waiting for this Bill to pass so they can be given powers appropriate to their roles and training.</p><p>If it is acceptable to confer all the powers of a constable on one type of volunteer, namely special constables, it is inconsistent to object in principle to conferring a narrower set of powers on other suitably trained volunteers. Chief officers are best placed to decide how to shape their workforce to meet local need and the reforms in the Bill enable them to do just that.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-19T13:37:46.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513049/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513049/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Police: Powers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for the Home Office of 24 March 2016, Official Report, column 209, on the Policing and Crime Bill, how her Department defines warranted in the context of warranted officers; and what assessment she has made of whether Clause 28 of the Policing and Crime Bill would give warranted powers to staff and volunteers.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","34148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513050","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>FRANK provides impartial, reliable and confidential information and advice about drug use. Public Health England (PHE) updates FRANK to reflect new and emerging patterns of drug use and is currently considering how best to enhance the service to remain in line with young people’s media habits and strengthen situational advice to reduce risks to young people.</p><p>Local authorities are responsible for commissioning drug and alcohol education prevention and treatment services to young people and parents. PHE supports local authorities in this work by providing a range of supportive guidance and materials, as well as bespoke data, value for money tools, topical briefings, and advice on good practice.</p><p>PHE is supporting a range of prevention and information programmes for young people and parents, including jointly funding Mentor UK’s Alcohol and Drug Education and Prevention Information Service which is a web-based platform for sharing information and resources aimed at schools and practitioners working in drug and alcohol prevention.</p><p>PHE also provides Rise Above, an online social marketing programme that aims to reduce the uptake of risky behaviours, including drug taking, by young people aged 11-16. It aims to give them the skills required to make better decisions in ‘risky’ situations to delay and prevent them from engaging in exploratory behaviours.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","33952","2016-04-19T14:14:32.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513050/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513050/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Drugs: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will review provision of the FRANK drug advice service to support reducing risks to young people.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","33945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513051","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>FRANK provides impartial, reliable and confidential information and advice about drug use. Public Health England (PHE) updates FRANK to reflect new and emerging patterns of drug use and is currently considering how best to enhance the service to remain in line with young people’s media habits and strengthen situational advice to reduce risks to young people.</p><p>Local authorities are responsible for commissioning drug and alcohol education prevention and treatment services to young people and parents. PHE supports local authorities in this work by providing a range of supportive guidance and materials, as well as bespoke data, value for money tools, topical briefings, and advice on good practice.</p><p>PHE is supporting a range of prevention and information programmes for young people and parents, including jointly funding Mentor UK’s Alcohol and Drug Education and Prevention Information Service which is a web-based platform for sharing information and resources aimed at schools and practitioners working in drug and alcohol prevention.</p><p>PHE also provides Rise Above, an online social marketing programme that aims to reduce the uptake of risky behaviours, including drug taking, by young people aged 11-16. It aims to give them the skills required to make better decisions in ‘risky’ situations to delay and prevent them from engaging in exploratory behaviours.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","33945","2016-04-19T14:14:32.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513051/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513051/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-14","Drugs: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government takes to provide drug harm reduction information for young people and parents.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","33952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513052","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Government has protected overall police spending for the coming Spending Review period in real terms, when local income is taken into account. This is an increase of up to £900 million in cash terms by 2019/20. The public can be confident that over the next four years the police will have the resources they need to carry on cutting crime, fighting terrorism and keeping the people of this country safe.</p><p>The proportion of police officers in frontline roles in England and Wales has increased from 89% in March 2010 to 92% in March 2015. Ultimately, decisions on the size and composition of a police force’s workforce are for individual chief officers and Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs).</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-19T13:37:08.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513052/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513052/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the grant settlement and provisional settlements for police forces up to 2019-20 on the ratio of officers to members of the public.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","34020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513053","Home Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Home Office has published information on the average cost of removal but this is not broken down by country or initial application type, and to do so would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>Further information can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/costs-involved-in-detaining-and-removing-illegal-migrants.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-19T17:14:26.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513053/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513053/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513053/answer/previousversion/56025","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513053/answer/previousversion/56025",,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Deportation: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much the Government spent on the enforced returns to Yemen of failed asylum claimants from that country in 2014.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","34006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513054","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Government takes the security of the energy sector very seriously and DECC works closely with industry, the police and the relevant agencies in order to make sure of a robust and proportionate security regime at energy sites across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>For reasons of national security it would not be appropriate to provide specific details about protective security programmes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-20T12:38:36.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513054/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513054/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-14","Power Stations: Pembrokeshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much funding her Department has provided for security at energy sites in Pembrokeshire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","33971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513055","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>There were 9 and 50 grants of asylum or an alternative form of protection, at initial decision, to Yemeni nationals in 2014 and 2015 respectively.</p><p>There were 34 and 43 refusals of asylum or an alternative form of protection, at initial decision, to Yemeni nationals in 2014 and 2015 respectively.</p><p>The Home Office publishes figures on asylum initial decisions by nationality in the quarterly Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics, October to December 2015, is available from:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34043","2016-04-21T11:58:07.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513055/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513055/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Asylum: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum claims from people from Yemen were granted in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","33993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513056","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>There were 66 and 111 asylum applications from Yemeni nationals in 2014 and 2015, respectively.</p><p>The Home Office publishes figures on asylum applications by nationality in the quarterly Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics, October to December 2015, is available from:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-october-to-december-2015.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34044","2016-04-21T11:57:18.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513056/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513056/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Asylum: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from Yemen claimed asylum in the UK in 2015.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","33994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513057","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>All escorting services to facilitate enforced returns are provided by the Home Office’s main contractor, Tascor. In 2014, detainee custody officers from the Pilgrims Group, who are sub-contracted by Tascor were used on one occasion on 23rd July to facilitate the enforced return of an individual to Yemen.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34015","2016-04-21T11:57:46.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513057/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513057/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Deportation: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which companies were contracted to facilitate enforced returns to Yemen for failed asylum seekers from that country in 2014.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","33995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513058","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>As at the end of 2014 and 2015 respectively, 66 and 73 asylum applications were pending a decision (initial decision, appeal or further review).</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly figures on asylum applications pending a decision in table as_01_q of the Immigration Statistics release. A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics October to December 2015, is available from:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a></p><p>Pending cases are those asylum applications, including fresh claims, lodged since 1 April 2006 which are still under consideration at the end of the reference period.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-21T11:57:30.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513058/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513058/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Asylum: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum claims from people from Yemen were pending for the duration of (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","33996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513059","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The attached table shows the number of enforced and voluntary departures for nationals of Yemen, who had claimed asylum at some point, in each of the last five years and their destination.</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of persons removed or departed voluntarily from the UK within Immigration Statistics. The data on removals and voluntary departures by destination are available in the latest release, Immigration Statistics: October to December 2015, table rv.06 from GOV.UK on the statistics web pages at: https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-21T12:00:05.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513059/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513059/answer","Table 33999.xlsx","Enforced & voluntary departures","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513059/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513059/answer/previousversion/56024","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513059/answer/previousversion/56024",,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Deportation: Yemen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people claiming asylum from Yemen have had that claim refused and have subsequently been removed from the UK in each of the last five years; and to which country each of those people have been removed.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","33999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513060","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service is a non-departmental public body which provides access to appropriate criminal record information for employers through its disclosure service for England and Wales. It also makes independent barring decisions about people who have harmed, or where there is considered to be a risk of harm to, a child or vulnerable person within the workplace. Given the sensitive nature of this work and the reliance on police forces to provide locally held intelligence, it would not be appropriate to introduce competition.</p><p>Whilst no assessment has been made of the affect of timeliness on the number of job opportunities which may have been lost, the impact which delays may have on applicants is recognised. The DBS is reliant on police forces completing their checks in a timely manner and is working closely with those forces whose performance does not meet turnaround time targets. In very exceptional cases, where it is apparent that a delay is likely to cause undue hardship to an applicant, the DBS will do all it can to expedite the process by raising an escalation with the relevant police force.</p><p>The average end to end time taken to complete a DBS check, including the time taken by police forces, is listed in following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Average calendar days for a disclosure to be processed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>11.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14/15</p></td><td><p>14.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15/16</p></td><td><p>14.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The proportion of checks which took longer than (a) eight weeks (b) 12 weeks and (c) six months is listed in the following table.</p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Disclosures which took longer than 8 weeks</p></td><td><p>Disclosures which took longer than 12 weeks</p></td><td><p>Disclosures which took longer than 6 Months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% of Disclosures</p></td><td><p>% of Disclosures</p></td><td><p>% of Disclosures</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>2.6%</p></td><td><p>0.8%</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14/15</p></td><td><p>4.9%</p></td><td><p>2.1%</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15/16</p></td><td><p>5.2%</p></td><td><p>3.5%</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","34032 ; 34033 ; 34035","2016-04-21T11:55:52.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513060/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513060/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-14","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what records the Government holds on how many job opportunities have been lost due to the time taken for Disclosure and Barring Service checks to be made.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","34034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513061","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-04-21T09:08:25.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513061/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513061/answer","UKSA response to 34047 .pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Death by Substances","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513061/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-14","Drugs: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make a comparative assessment of how many deaths were caused by new psychoactive substances in the UK, Ireland and Poland in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","34047"
