"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512627","Department of Health","false","2016-04-20","<p>Refractive eye surgery is regulated through providers being registered with the Care Quality Commission (CQC) and doctors carrying out the surgery must be registered with the General Medical Council.</p><p>Once the Royal College of Ophthalmologists refractive surgery standards are published, the General Medical Council would expect a doctor to be aware of them. When carrying out inspections and assessments of services, the CQC would also expect a provider to be following best practice guidance, which would include the standards published by the Royal College of Ophthalmologists.</p><p>These processes are well established and so the Department would not have a direct role in assisting in the implementation of the refractive surgery standards. However, the Department will maintain an interest in the consultation and the work of the Royal College of Ophthalmologists in this area.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","33724","2016-04-20T09:44:04.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512627/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512627/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-13","Eyesight: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how his Department plans to assist with the implementation of new refractive surgery standards being drawn up by the Royal College of Ophthalmologists.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","33723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512628","Department of Health","false","2016-04-20","<p>Refractive eye surgery is regulated through providers being registered with the Care Quality Commission (CQC) and doctors carrying out the surgery must be registered with the General Medical Council.</p><p>Once the Royal College of Ophthalmologists refractive surgery standards are published, the General Medical Council would expect a doctor to be aware of them. When carrying out inspections and assessments of services, the CQC would also expect a provider to be following best practice guidance, which would include the standards published by the Royal College of Ophthalmologists.</p><p>These processes are well established and so the Department would not have a direct role in assisting in the implementation of the refractive surgery standards. However, the Department will maintain an interest in the consultation and the work of the Royal College of Ophthalmologists in this area.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","33723","2016-04-20T09:44:04.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512628/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512628/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-13","Eyesight: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what contribution his Department plans to make to the Royal College of Ophthalmologists' consultation on raising standards for refractive surgery.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","33724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512629","Department of Health","false","2016-04-18","<p>In response to the Review recommendations, the Government established a large-scale two year data collection exercise to find out more about palliative care costs, with the aim of working towards a fairer, more transparent funding system for palliative care.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2013, NHS England assumed responsibility for this work. The data collection concluded in 2014 and NHS England published a palliative care development currency in February 2015. Over 2015/16 the currency has been tested and refined in a number of local areas around the country. During 2016, NHS England will engage with key stakeholders on the results of this testing and make a definitive set of currencies available for use in April 2017. The currencies will allow commissioners and providers of specialist end of life care to ensure the best services are being provided to meet people’s needs regardless of care setting.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-04-18T16:16:30.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512629/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512629/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-13","Palliative Care Funding Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government has taken in response to the Palliative Care Funding Review, published in July 2011.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","33753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512630","Department of Health","false","2016-04-18","<p>The information requested is available from the web link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2015/06/Incomplete-Provider-Feb16-XLS-3690K-hjkhj.xls" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2015/06/Incomplete-Provider-Feb16-XLS-3690K-hjkhj.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>Patients have a legal right, set out in the NHS Constitution, to start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks from referral for non-urgent conditions. The referral to treatment (RTT) waiting time standard is that 92% of patients still waiting to start treatment (incomplete pathways) should have been waiting no more than 18 weeks from referral at the end of each month.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of February 2016 Warrington and Halton Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust reported 24,902 patients waiting to start consultant-led treatment were on an incomplete RTT pathway. 23,069 (92.6%) of these were waiting within 18 weeks from referral, while 1,833 patients were waiting more than 18 weeks. It is not possible to identify how many patients were waiting for surgical procedures.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-04-18T16:17:18.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512630/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512630/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-13","Surgery: Halton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many patients from Halton Borough have been waiting for more than 18 weeks for a surgical procedure.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","33758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512631","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>There have been no representations from National Health Service staff who feel they are being harassed outside NHS buildings by protesters.</p><p>Although protesters are democratically entitled to make their views known on abortion and other issues and can do so outside NHS hospitals and other NHS buildings, we would condemn any harassment of NHS staff, patients and others. We would expect NHS trusts, as responsible for providing a safe environment for all using their facilities, to work with the Police and other agencies as appropriate to ensure they have adequate arrangements in place to prevent harassment of staff and patients. If staff are subject to criminal activity such as physical assaults, these should be reported so that employers can take appropriate action.</p><p>Currently, NHS trusts have access to Security Incident Reporting Systems which helps NHS Protect measure the nature and scale of security incidents across the NHS, not just those involving physical assaults on staff but also those involving non-physical abuse and theft of/damage to NHS assets.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","33736 ; 33737","2016-04-19T10:48:38.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512631/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512631/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-13","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has received any representations from NHS staff who feel they are being harassed outside NHS buildings by protesters.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","33735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512632","Department of Health","false","2016-04-19","<p>There have been no representations from National Health Service staff who feel they are being harassed outside NHS buildings by protesters.</p><p>Although protesters are democratically entitled to make their views known on abortion and other issues and can do so outside NHS hospitals and other NHS buildings, we would condemn any harassment of NHS staff, patients and others. We would expect NHS trusts, as responsible for providing a safe environment for all using their facilities, to work with the Police and other agencies as appropriate to ensure they have adequate arrangements in place to prevent harassment of staff and patients. If staff are subject to criminal activity such as physical assaults, these should be reported so that employers can take appropriate action.</p><p>Currently, NHS trusts have access to Security Incident Reporting Systems which helps NHS Protect measure the nature and scale of security incidents across the NHS, not just those involving physical assaults on staff but also those involving non-physical abuse and theft of/damage to NHS assets.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","33735 ; 33737","2016-04-19T10:48:39.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512632/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512632/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-13","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure patients accessing NHS abortions in England are not harassed by protestors outside NHS hospitals.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","33736"
